"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145949","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-03","<p>Improving humanitarian and commercial access in Yemen is one of the UK’s top priorities. The UK is actively raising humanitarian concerns with all parties, calling on them to comply with UN Security Council Resolution 2451 and facilitate safe, rapid, and unhindered access for humanitarian and commercial supplies, including through Aden Port and airports. The UK continues to encourage vital access for food, fuel, and medicine by providing £1.3 million to help the UN’s Verification and Inspection Mechanism to facilitate commercial imports into Hodeidah and Saleef ports by giving the Coalition confidence that weapons are not coming in on commercial ships.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-03T10:30:27.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145949/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145949/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-25","Yemen: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has held with his counterparts in (a) the Government of Saudi Arabia and (b) the Government of Yemen on (i) opening Sana’a International airport, (ii) implementing a UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism to facilitate traffic through the airport and (iii) facilitating direct international flights for aid workers, journalists, humanitarian aid and seriously ill people.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145950","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-03","<p>We consistently urge all parties, including the Houthis, to engage constructively with the UN Special Envoy. A nationwide ceasefire will only have an effect on the ground if it is underpinned by a political deal between the conflict parties. A political solution is the only way to bring long-term stability to Yemen and to address the worsening humanitarian crisis. The Yemeni parties must engage constructively and in good faith with the UN Special Envoy to overcome obstacles to progress and find a political settlement to end the conflict.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","290648","2019-10-03T10:32:22.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145950/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145950/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-25","Yemen: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to open direct talks with the Houthi leadership in Sana’a to find a solution to the conflict in Yemen; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145951","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-30","<p>Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is provided in England through the three year PrEP Impact Trial. Participation in the trial is on a voluntary basis and it is for clinics and local authorities to decide the number of allocated places they can accept.</p><p>The Department is continuing to work closely with NHS England and NHS Improvement, Public Health England and local authorities to plan for a seamless transition from the PrEP Impact Trial to routine commissioning.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-09-30T17:02:05.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145951/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145951/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-25","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to support local authorities to deliver Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) for HIV.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","291079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145952","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-03","<p>We consistently urge all parties, including the Houthis, to engage constructively with the UN Special Envoy. A nationwide ceasefire will only have an effect on the ground if it is underpinned by a political deal between the conflict parties. A political solution is the only way to bring long-term stability to Yemen and to address the worsening humanitarian crisis. The Yemeni parties must engage constructively and in good faith with the UN Special Envoy to overcome obstacles to progress and find a political settlement to end the conflict.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","290647","2019-10-03T10:32:22.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145952/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145952/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-25","Yemen: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has held with his Saudi Arabian and Government of Yemen counterparts on holding direct talks with the Houthi leadership to broker a nationwide ceasefire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145953","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-03","<p>The UK supports the UN Group of Eminent Experts (GEE) and we welcome the renewal of its mandate. It is important to give the Group more time to fully examine the conflict and to ensure that their conclusions accurately reflect the conduct of all parties. The UK urges all parties to the conflict to cooperate with the GEE and to promote and protect human rights in Yemen. We are disappointed that the Group has not had the necessary access to the conflict zone, or been able to visit many of the countries that are engaged in the conflict. We encourage engagement with the Group as a means of ensuring that their conclusions are as well informed as possible, and that they reflect the views of all.</p><p>​</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-03T10:35:03.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145953/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145953/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-25","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has held with his (a) Saudi Arabian, (b) Emirati and (c) Government of Yemen counterparts to facilitate access for the UN Humans Rights Council Panel of Eminent Experts to all regions of Yemen including Sana’a.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145954","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-30","<p>In the north west of England, the NHS Business Services Authority currently occupies three properties, two offices and one warehouse.</p><p>In the north east of England, NHS Business Services Authority currently occupies four properties, two offices and two warehouses, and manages one property on behalf of the Counter Fraud Authority.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-09-30T13:58:25.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145954/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145954/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-25","NHS Business Services Authority: North East and North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2019 to Question 285061, how many offices the NHS Business Service Authority has in the (a) North East and (b) North West.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","290694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145955","Department for Education","false","2019-10-07","<p>The number of proportion of children in primary schools in Wallasey constituency who were eligible and claiming free school meals (FSM) is provided in the attached table.</p><p>Since April 2018, protections have been in place for FSM eligibility while Universal Credit is introduced nationwide. This has been the main driver in the increase in the proportion of pupils eligible for and claiming free school meals as pupils continue to become eligible but fewer pupils stop being eligible.</p><p>This data is published at national and school level in the underlying data of the annual ‘Schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical release. The 2019 publication is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019</a>.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-10-07T06:32:35.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145955/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145955/answer","290695_Number_and_proportion_of_FSM_students_since_2010.xls","290695_Number_and_proportion_of_FSM_students_since_2010.xls","290695_Table","290695_Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145955/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145955/answer/previousversion/136153","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-09-25","Free School Meals: Wallasey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in primary schools in Wallasey constituency were eligible for free school meals in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","290695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145956","Department for International Development","false","2019-10-03","<p>According to the UN’s 2019 Humanitarian Needs Overview, only 22 per cent of rural and 46 per cent of urban populations are connected to partially functioning public water networks, and trucked water is mostly unregulated and expensive.</p><p> </p><p>Where functioning public water and sanitation systems exist, coverage remains poor, with a majority of governorates and districts reportedly showing coverage below 60% of the populations they serve.</p><p> </p><p>The international humanitarian response, including funding from the UK, ensures that sustained water delivery reaches an average of approximately 3.5 million people per month whilst sustained sanitation delivery reaches an average of approximately 1.7 million people per month.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-03T16:06:33.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145956/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145956/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-25","Yemen: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate he has made of the operability of urban water and sanitation plants by each governorate in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>On 18 June 2019, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office team in the Export Control Joint Unit received information that RSLF troops were deployed in Yemen.</p><p>​</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-09-30T14:41:32.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145957/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-25","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the letter of 16 September 2019 from the Secretary of State for International Trade letter to the chair of the Committees on Arms Export Controls, when his Department knew that RSLF troops were deployed in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","291080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145958","Department for Education","false","2019-09-30","<p>The number of apprenticeship starts in Wallasey local authority in each year since 2005/06 can be found in the table attached.</p><p>Figures for 2011/12 onwards are not directly comparable to 2010/11 or prior years as a Single Individualised Learner Record collection system was introduced in 2011/12.</p><p>More detailed breakdowns of starts in local areas, by characteristics such as age, level and sector subject area are available in the further education data library: <br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships</a>.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-09-30T16:29:26.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145958/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145958/answer","290696_Apprenticeship_starts_in_Wallasey_by_academic_year_2010-11_to_2018-19 .xlsx","290696_Apprenticeship_starts_in_Wallasey_by_academic_year_2010-11_to_2018-19 .xlsx","290696_Table","290696_Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145958/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-25","Apprentices: Wallasey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many apprenticeships starts there were in Wallasey constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","290696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145959","Attorney General","false","2019-10-04","<p>No estimate has been made of the total costs of the prorogation litigation, which only recently concluded. We expect to know the final figures in November.</p><p> </p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-10-04T11:52:14.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145959/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145959/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2019-09-25","Prorogation: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much was spent by the UK Government in undertaking legal action in the (a) Cherry and others (Respondents) v Advocate General for Scotland (Appellant) (Scotland), (b) R (on the application of Miller) (Appellant) v The Prime Minister (Respondent) in the Supreme Court, (c) case number CO/3385/2019 in the High Court, (d) reclaiming motion by Joanna Cherry QC MP and others against the Advocate General in the Outer Court of Scotland and (e) (First) Joanna Cherry QC MP and others for judicial review in the Outer Court of Scotland cases.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","290699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145960","Department for International Development","false","2019-10-03","<p>The UK does not collect comprehensive information on the number of Government of Yemen workers receiving salary payments.</p><p> </p><p>However, we welcome reports of the Government of Yemen making recent progress towards paying public-sector salaries across more of the country, including in Hodeidah governorate and other Houthi-controlled areas.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to encourage the Government of Yemen to resume the full and regular payment of public-sector salaries in all areas of the country.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-03T16:07:27.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145960/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145960/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-25","Yemen: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate he has made of the proportion of Yemeni Government workers by each Governorate in receipt of salary payments; and what the regularity of those payments is.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145961","Department for Education","false","2019-10-07","<p>The information requested by constituency level is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Department does publish the proportion of students who entered higher education by age 19 who were eligible for free school meals at age 15 in state-funded and special schools at a local authority level. This information is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/widening-participation-in-higher-education-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/widening-participation-in-higher-education-2018</a>.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-10-07T18:02:30.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145961/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145961/answer","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145961/answer/previousversion/136152","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","60","Education","Education","2019-09-25","Free School Meals: Wallasey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in secondary schools in Wallasey eligible for free school meals went on to higher education in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","290697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145962","Department for International Development","false","2019-10-03","<p>As of 29 September, according to data from the UN Verification Inspection Mechanism (UNVIM), ten vessels carrying cargos of fuel were awaiting to berth at Hodeidah port.</p><p> </p><p>These vessels were carrying a total estimated volume of over 212,000 Metric Tonnes of fuel – the equivalent of approximately a month’s average fuel imports through Hodeidah port. We cannot estimate the value of this fuel as the overall value depends on the individual commercial arrangements made in each case.</p><p> </p><p>As of 29 September, no issues were reported by UNVIM on vessels carrying food, medical supplies and other cargo.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-03T16:08:08.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145962/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145962/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-25","Yemen: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate he has made of the (a) monetary value and (b) tonnage of commercial imports of (i) food, (ii) fuel, (iii) medical supplies and (iv) essential materials awaiting transshipment using letters of credit issued by the Government of Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","290652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145963","Home Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>No meetings with representatives of Merseyside Fire and Rescue Service have taken place.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-09-30T14:13:02.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145963/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145963/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-25","Merseyside Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Minister of State for Crime, Policing and the Fire Service has met representatives of the Merseyside Fire and Rescue Service.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","290698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145964","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-09-30","<p>The Cyber Skills Immediate Impact Fund encourages a sector-led approach to stimulating the cyber security retraining ecosystem in a sustainable way. It is designed to increase the number and diversity of individuals pursuing a career in the cyber security profession. Launched in 2018, the Cyber Skills Immediate Impact Fund announced its third funding round on 14 August 2019.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently running an open grant competition for proposed initiatives to apply for funding. We expect to support several new initiatives in this round of funding, working closely with employers to maximise the employment prospects of the individuals benefiting from the training programmes. Over 400 people have already benefited from training supported by previous funding rounds, and our objective is that greater numbers will benefit as the businesses we partner with further invest in this sector. The outcome of this programme will be reported in due course.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman",,"2019-09-30T14:49:41.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145964/answer","Biography information for Matt Warman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145964/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-25","Cybercrime: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to her Department's announcement entitled New boost to increase diversity in nation’s cyber security industry published on 14 August 2019, what target her Department has set on the number of people who will be assisted by the third round of funding from the Cyber Skills Immediate Impact Fund.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","291081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145965","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-09-30","<p>We are working with industry stakeholders and all interested parties to ensure that any unintended consequences of implementation of the DNS over HTTPS protocol are addressed. Recommendations on a course of action will be developed in due course.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman",,"2019-09-30T15:26:30.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145965/answer","Biography information for Matt Warman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145965/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-25","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 22 July 2019 to Question 277853, whether her Department has set a timescale for the publication of guidance on the use of DNS over HTTPS.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","291082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145966","Department for International Trade","false","2019-09-30","<p>As the Secretary of State said in her statement to Parliament on 26<sup>th</sup> September, as soon as the issue was brought to her attention on the 12<sup>th</sup> September, she took immediate action:</p><ul><li>Taking immediate steps to inform the Court and Parliament;</li><li>Putting in place immediate, interim procedures to make sure the error could not happen again;</li><li>Instigating a complete and full internal review of all licences granted for Saudi Arabia and its Coalition partners since 20 June;</li><li>Asking the Permanent Secretary to commission, on her behalf, a full independent investigation.</li></ul><p>This investigation will: (i) establish the precise circumstances in which these licences were granted; (ii) establish whether any other licences have been granted in breach of the Undertaking to the Court or the commitment to Parliament; and (iii) confirm that procedures are in place to ensure that no further such breaches can occur. The Director General Policy Group at the Department for Work and Pensions has been appointed to lead this investigation.</p><p> </p><p>During the course of this investigation, licence applications for Saudi Arabia and its Coalition partners will be referred to a new weekly meeting of senior officials from DIT, FCO and MOD. (Some will have been refused by this point, for example where they fail to meet one or more of the Consolidated Criteria.) This meeting will reach a recommendation for Ministers as to whether applications are within the scope of the Undertaking and the Parliamentary Statement, applying a further checklist of questions which are designed to ensure that: (i) current and full information is available to enable an assessment of whether the items in question are for possible use in the conflict in Yemen; and (ii) if there has been any change in circumstances in the conflict in Yemen, this is properly included in the assessment. All recommendations to grant licences for the export of items to Saudi Arabia and its Coalition partners will now be referred to Ministers for decision.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","290582","2019-09-30T15:10:52.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145966/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145966/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-09-25","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps she plans to take to ensure that her Department does not violate the court order on banning the issuing of new export licences to Saudi Arabia and its coalition partners for arms that could be used in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","291083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145967","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-10-08","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman",,"2019-10-08T16:35:32.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145967/answer","Biography information for Matt Warman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145967/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-25","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent communications he has received from each Gov.UK Verify provider on their continued participation in the scheme.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","291084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145968","Department for International Trade","false","2019-09-30","<p>As the Secretary of State said in her statement to Parliament on 26<sup>th</sup> September, as soon as the issue was brought to her attention on the 12<sup>th</sup> September, she took immediate action:</p><ul><li>Taking immediate steps to inform the Court and Parliament;</li><li>Putting in place immediate, interim procedures to make sure the error could not happen again;</li><li>Instigating a complete and full internal review of all licences granted for Saudi Arabia and its Coalition partners since 20 June;</li><li>Asking the Permanent Secretary to commission, on her behalf, a full independent investigation.</li></ul><p>This investigation will: (i) establish the precise circumstances in which these licences were granted; (ii) establish whether any other licences have been granted in breach of the Undertaking to the Court or the commitment to Parliament; and (iii) confirm that procedures are in place to ensure that no further such breaches can occur. The Director General Policy Group at the Department for Work and Pensions has been appointed to lead this investigation.</p><p> </p><p>During the course of this investigation, licence applications for Saudi Arabia and its Coalition partners will be referred to a new weekly meeting of senior officials from DIT, FCO and MOD. (Some will have been refused by this point, for example where they fail to meet one or more of the Consolidated Criteria.) This meeting will reach a recommendation for Ministers as to whether applications are within the scope of the Undertaking and the Parliamentary Statement, applying a further checklist of questions which are designed to ensure that: (i) current and full information is available to enable an assessment of whether the items in question are for possible use in the conflict in Yemen; and (ii) if there has been any change in circumstances in the conflict in Yemen, this is properly included in the assessment. All recommendations to grant licences for the export of items to Saudi Arabia and its Coalition partners will now be referred to Ministers for decision.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","291083","2019-09-30T15:10:52.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145968/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145968/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-09-25","Arms Trade: Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to the Secretary of State’s letter of 16 September 2019 to the Chair of the Committees on Arms Export Controls, what steps the Government is taking to review the way in which information is exchanged with the Joint Export Control Unit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","290582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>In line with its formal role in providing advice to DIT on the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) provided its advice on the three applications in question for export to Saudi Arabia on 2 April and 6 June 2019. On 18 June 2019, the FCO team in the Export Control Joint Unit received information from the British Embassy in Riyadh that RSLF troops were deployed in Yemen. At this stage, the FCO was unaware that the licences had not already been issued by DIT and this was before the undertaking to the court on 20 June.</p><p>​</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","290585","2019-09-30T14:35:23.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145969/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145969/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-25","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Secretary of State for International Trade’s letter of 16 September 2019 to the Chair of the Committees on Arms Export Control, when the British Embassy in Riyadh became aware that Royal Saudi Land Forces were operational in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","290583"
