"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146353","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-07","<p>The average length of time between the receipt of Ministry of Defence tender submissions and contract awards is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie",,"2019-10-07T14:07:44.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146353/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146353/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-25","Ministry of Defence: Contracts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the average length of time between the receipt of Ministry of Defence tender submissions and contract awards made in the (1) 2009/10, (2) 2014/5, and (3) 2018/19, financial years.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL17848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146354","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-07","<p>The number of Ministry of Defence invitations to tender that have ended in a failure to award any contract is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie",,"2019-10-07T14:07:34.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146354/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146354/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-25","Ministry of Defence: Contracts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many Ministry of Defence invitations to tender ended in a failure to award any contract in the (1) 2009/10, (2) 2014/15, and (3) 2018/19, financial years.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL17849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146355","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-07","<p>Pending the outcome of a competition to award a long-term support contract for the 30mm gun capability on in-service Royal Navy ships, interim technical support is being provided by MSI Defence Systems Limited. Arrangements are under way to award a further interim contract to provide additional support, including the provision of spares and necessary design modifications.</p><p>The 30mm gun capability on the Type 26 Frigates will be supplied to the Ministry of Defence by BAE Systems. The Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers are not fitted with 30mm guns.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie","HL17851 ; HL17852","2019-10-07T14:06:54.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146355/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146355/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-25","Warships: Weapons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether a service and support contract is in place to support the 30mm guns on naval ships.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL17850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146356","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-07","<p>Pending the outcome of a competition to award a long-term support contract for the 30mm gun capability on in-service Royal Navy ships, interim technical support is being provided by MSI Defence Systems Limited. Arrangements are under way to award a further interim contract to provide additional support, including the provision of spares and necessary design modifications.</p><p>The 30mm gun capability on the Type 26 Frigates will be supplied to the Ministry of Defence by BAE Systems. The Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers are not fitted with 30mm guns.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie","HL17850 ; HL17852","2019-10-07T14:06:54.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146356/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146356/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-25","Warships: Weapons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which company produces spares and provides necessary design modifications for in-service 30mm guns on naval ships.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL17851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146357","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-07","<p>Pending the outcome of a competition to award a long-term support contract for the 30mm gun capability on in-service Royal Navy ships, interim technical support is being provided by MSI Defence Systems Limited. Arrangements are under way to award a further interim contract to provide additional support, including the provision of spares and necessary design modifications.</p><p>The 30mm gun capability on the Type 26 Frigates will be supplied to the Ministry of Defence by BAE Systems. The Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers are not fitted with 30mm guns.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie","HL17850 ; HL17851","2019-10-07T14:06:54.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146357/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146357/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-25","Warships: Weapons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which company supplies 30mm guns on the two aircraft carriers and Type 26 frigates.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL17852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146358","Home Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes statistics on the number of police officers who are suspended (as at 31<sup>st</sup> March each year) and the number who are on restricted or adjusted duties in each police force in England and Wales on an annual basis.</p><p>These data are published in the ‘Police workforce, England and Wales’ statistical bulletins. The latest data available on the number of police officers who are suspended, as at 31 March 2019, can be found in Table W2 of the accompanying Data Tables:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/831666/police-workforce-mar19-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/831666/police-workforce-mar19-tables.ods</a></p><p>Data on the number of police officers who were suspended as at 31 March in each of the last 5 years in each police constabulary can be found in Police Workforce Absence open data:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/817736/open-data-table-police-workforce-absence.ods" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/817736/open-data-table-police-workforce-absence.ods</a></p><p>The latest data available on the number of police officers who are on restricted or adjusted duties, as at 31 March 2019, can be found in Table W3 of the accompanying Data Tables:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/831666/police-workforce-mar19-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/831666/police-workforce-mar19-tables.ods</a></p><p>It is not possible to separate out officers on restricted duties from those on adjusted duties.</p><p>The Home Office does not collect data on the number of other police employees who are suspended or on adjusted/restricted duties.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","290995","2019-09-30T14:18:19.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146358/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146358/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-25","Police: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) police officers and (b) other police employees were subject to (i) suspension from duties and (ii) restricted duties in each of the last five years in (A) each police constabulary and (B) the police force as a whole.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","291167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146359","Home Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>The Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC) determines the information that police forces are required to collect on police complaints. The data is published by the IOPC on its website and through an annual Police Complaints Statistics report.</p><p><a href="https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/statistics/complaints_statistics_2017_18.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/statistics/complaints_statistics_2017_18.pdf</a>.</p><p>The data includes the number of complaints received by each force, the types of complaint and the time taken to deal with them.</p><p>The Government has developed a comprehensive package of reforms to the police complaints system to increase transparency and the timeliness with which complaints are handled. These reforms are set out in the Policing and Crime Act 2017 and will be implemented early next year, Parliamentary time permitting.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","290996 ; 290999 ; 291000 ; 291169 ; 291170","2019-09-30T14:24:35.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146359/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146359/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-25","Police: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what data her Department holds on the time taken by police constabularies to resolve complaints involving police officers and other police force employees.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","291168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146360","Home Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>The Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC) determines the information that police forces are required to collect on police complaints. The data is published by the IOPC on its website and through an annual Police Complaints Statistics report.</p><p><a href="https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/statistics/complaints_statistics_2017_18.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/statistics/complaints_statistics_2017_18.pdf</a>.</p><p>The data includes the number of complaints received by each force, the types of complaint and the time taken to deal with them.</p><p>The Government has developed a comprehensive package of reforms to the police complaints system to increase transparency and the timeliness with which complaints are handled. These reforms are set out in the Policing and Crime Act 2017 and will be implemented early next year, Parliamentary time permitting.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","290996 ; 290999 ; 291000 ; 291168 ; 291170","2019-09-30T14:24:35.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146360/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146360/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-25","Police: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what obligations each police constabulary has to collect data on (a) the number of complaints received in its force area and (b) the type of complaints.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","291169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146361","Home Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>The Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC) determines the information that police forces are required to collect on police complaints. The data is published by the IOPC on its website and through an annual Police Complaints Statistics report.</p><p><a href="https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/statistics/complaints_statistics_2017_18.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Documents/statistics/complaints_statistics_2017_18.pdf</a>.</p><p>The data includes the number of complaints received by each force, the types of complaint and the time taken to deal with them.</p><p>The Government has developed a comprehensive package of reforms to the police complaints system to increase transparency and the timeliness with which complaints are handled. These reforms are set out in the Policing and Crime Act 2017 and will be implemented early next year, Parliamentary time permitting.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","290996 ; 290999 ; 291000 ; 291168 ; 291169","2019-09-30T14:24:35.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146361/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146361/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-25","Police: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to increase the (a) transparency and (b) speed of police complaints handling.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","291170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146362","Home Office","false","2019-09-30","<p>This is an operational matter for Hampshire Constabulary. The Home Office does not comment on on-ging investigations.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-09-30T15:03:56.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146362/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146362/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-25","Police: Basingstoke","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the investigation into allegations of discrimination at the North Hampshire Police Investigation Centre in Basingstoke that commenced in February 2018 will be (a) completed and (b) made public.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","291171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146754","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-02","<p>The Department for Communities in Northern Ireland is responsible for the delivery of the various mitigation schemes relating to welfare reform in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>A decision to extend mitigations beyond March 2020 would be a matter for an incoming Minister for Communities in a restored Northern Ireland Executive.</p>","Skipton and Ripon","Julian Smith",,"2019-10-02T16:12:44.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146754/answer","Biography information for Julian Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146754/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-09-25","Welfare State: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether the welfare mitigation package for people in Northern Ireland will be extended beyond March 2020.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","291585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145439","Home Office","false","2019-10-08","<p>Immediately after exit, EU citizens can continue to cross the border using their passport or national identity card. They will be able to use e-Gates if they are travelling on a biometric passport.</p><p>EU citizens will not be routinely asked to prove that they have been granted status under the EU Settlement Scheme after EU Exit in order to re-enter the UK but systems will be in place to allow border officials to make such checks where necessary. There are established contingency processes and procedures in the event of any interruption to systems at the border which border officials are familiar with.</p><p>Once the new points based immigration system is fully introduced, Border Force will be able to identify those individuals granted status digitally without the need for the individual to provide evidence.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2019-10-08T15:00:31.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145439/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145439/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-24","Immigration: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department has taken for EEA nationals’ settlement status to be verified by border officials after the UK exits the EU in the event that the secure online service is inaccessible due to (a) temporary system failure, (b) planned system maintenance and (c) cyber-attack.","false","Biography information for Mr Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi","Slough","Mr Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi","290438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145440","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-10-01","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework makes clear that when setting parking standards for residential and non residential developments local authorities will need to take into account the need to ensure an adequate provision of spaces for charging plug-in and other ultra-low emission vehicles. It also makes clear that applications for development should be designed to enable charging of plug-in and other ultra-low emission vehicles in safe, accessible and convenient locations.<em> <br> <br></em>The Government is consulting on whether to introduce new building regulations requirements to set a minimum standard for the provision of electric vehicle chargepoints in the following circumstances, where the building has associated car parking</p><p>- when constructing a new building<br>- when undergoing major renovation of a residential building<br>- for existing non-residential buildings</p><p>The consultation is open until 7 October and can be found here: (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/electric-vehicle-chargepoints-in-residential-and-non-residential-buildings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/electric-vehicle-chargepoints-in-residential-and-non-residential-buildings</a> )</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey","290320","2019-10-01T15:09:28.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145440/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145440/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-24","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the requirement for electric vehicle charging points on new developments is.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","290319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145441","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-10-01","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework makes clear that when setting parking standards for residential and non residential developments local authorities will need to take into account the need to ensure an adequate provision of spaces for charging plug-in and other ultra-low emission vehicles. It also makes clear that applications for development should be designed to enable charging of plug-in and other ultra-low emission vehicles in safe, accessible and convenient locations.<em> <br> <br></em>The Government is consulting on whether to introduce new building regulations requirements to set a minimum standard for the provision of electric vehicle chargepoints in the following circumstances, where the building has associated car parking</p><p>- when constructing a new building<br>- when undergoing major renovation of a residential building<br>- for existing non-residential buildings</p><p>The consultation is open until 7 October and can be found here: (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/electric-vehicle-chargepoints-in-residential-and-non-residential-buildings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/electric-vehicle-chargepoints-in-residential-and-non-residential-buildings</a> )</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey","290319","2019-10-01T15:09:28.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145441/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145441/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-24","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of electric vehicle charging points provided on new residential developments.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","290320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145442","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-02","<p>Defra recognises the role of blue carbon ecosystems including seagrasses, to remove carbon from the atmosphere and store it for long periods of time as well as providing multiple other benefits such as storm protection, improving water quality, and benefiting biodiversity and fisheries.</p><p> </p><p>Our Marine Climate Change Impacts Partnership have assessed how seagrass habitats can be managed and protected in a changing climate (<a href="http://www.mccip.org.uk/media/1816/mccip-seagrass.pdf" target="_blank">mccip-seagrass report card</a>).</p><p> </p><p>Nature-based solutions, including the protection and restoration of blue carbon ecosystems like seagrass, are key to tackling climate change and averting its impacts.</p>","Taunton Deane","Rebecca Pow",,"2019-10-02T16:13:15.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145442/answer","Biography information for Rebecca Pow","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145442/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-09-24","Seagrass: Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the merits of the use of underwater seagrass to capture and store carbon from the atmosphere.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","290321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145443","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-02","<p>The Department’s consultation on changes to the reimbursement of pharmacy contractors has now closed and responses are being analysed. The impact assessment that was published alongside the consultation document will be updated with information provided by respondents to the consultation which includes dispensing doctors and bodies representing them. No separate impact assessment will be undertaken by NHS England and NHS Improvement in relation to the consultation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-02T11:11:12.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145443/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145443/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-24","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September to Question 284853 on prescription fees and charging, whether NHS England will publish its own impact assessment on the effects of the consultation on dispensing doctors.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","290322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145444","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-30","<p>National statistics on Clostridioides difficile (C. difficile) infection do not include the number or rate of recurrent cases in the United Kingdom therefore it is not possible to estimate the cost of treating patients with recurrent C. difficile to the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-09-30T17:10:53.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145444/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145444/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-24","Clostridium: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the cost to the NHS of treating patients with recurrent C-difficile infection.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","290339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145445","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-30","<p>Data on the number of patients on antibiotics who developed antibiotic-associated diarrhoea (AAD), clostridium difficile infections (CDI), or clostridium difficile-associated disease are not available in the format requested.</p><p>Public Health England publishes data on the number of CDIs which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/clostridium-difficile-infection-annual-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/clostridium-difficile-infection-annual-data</a></p><p>Data are not collected on the number of people with AAD.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-09-30T17:10:21.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145445/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145445/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-24","Antibiotics: Diarrhoea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what data his Department holds on the number of patients on antibiotics who developed (a) AAD and (b) CDI/CDAD.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","290340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145446","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-02","<p>Public Health England (PHE) does not collect data on community-acquired Clostridium difficile infections (CDI). However, PHE collects data on community-onset CDI. Community-onset CDI are those cases occurring without or within two days of a hospital admission.</p><p>In approximately half of the community-onset CDI cases (50.1% or 3,706/399 cases), the patient was either admitted to hospital at the time of the first positive sample or admitted shortly afterwards.</p><p>It should be noted that this information is in part reliant on completion of an optional data field and therefore ascertainment may not be optimal. PHE does not collect information on the reasons of the patient being admitted to the hospital. Therefore, in some cases the admission to hospital may have been for other reasons than the CDI.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-02T16:04:04.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145446/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145446/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-24","Clostridium: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of community-acquired c-difficile infections require hospitalisation.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","290341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145447","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-01","<p>Data on the proportion of patients with an antibiotic prescription who were subsequently admitted to hospital are not available.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-01T09:55:28.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145447/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145447/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-24","Antibiotics: Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of prescriptions for antibiotics issued in the last (a) 12 months and (b) five years; and what proportion of those patients were subsequently admitted to hospital.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","290342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145448","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-02","<p>If livestock move on to a farm the standstill rule requires the farmer to retain all livestock on their farm, in most instances for six days, before being able to move any of them off again. There are a number of exemptions such as moves to slaughter. The aim is to find the balance between reducing the risk of undetected disease spread and the need to trade.</p><p>In 2018, officials discussed the rule with representatives of the industry. It was agreed that a review of the rule would need to await the delivery of the new Livestock Information Service (LIS) as this will be a key source of movement data. The LIS will replace the current separate species movement reporting services in England. Delivery is planned to commence in late 2020 and should take approximately 2 years. Any consequent proposals to change the standstill arrangements will be assessed on an epidemiological risk basis and will be subject to public consultation.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-10-02T15:33:52.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145448/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145448/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-09-24","Livestock: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to review the six day standstill rule.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","290439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145449","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-30","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) does not allocate funding for specific disease areas. The level of research spend in a particular area, such as cancer, is driven by factors including scientific potential and the number and scale of successful funding applications.</p><p>The NIHR’s expenditure on cancer research constitutes the largest investment in a disease area, and expenditure since 2009 is set out in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-09-30T16:41:14.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145449/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145449/answer","PQ290349 attachment.docx","PQ290349 attachment.docx","PQ290349 table","PQ290349 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145449/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-24","Cancer: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding the Government allocated to cancer research in each financial year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","290349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145450","Home Office","false","2019-10-03","<p>It is illegal to sell knives and certain articles with blade or point to anyone under 18 in England and Wales, by virtue of the Criminal Justice Act 1988. To go further in preventing the sale of knives to under 18s, the Offensive Weapons Act 2019 includes a provision that will stop knives from being sent to residential addresses after they are bought online, unless the seller has arrangements in place with the delivery company to ensure that the product would not be delivered into the hands of a person under 18.</p><p>The definition of knife in the Criminal Justice Act includes any other article which has a blade or which is sharply pointed and made or adapted for use in causing injury to a person. These words carry their normal meaning and we expect retailers to act responsibly and to consider carefully whether an item could commonly be defined as a knife.</p><p> </p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-10-03T16:48:42.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145450/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145450/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-24","Knives: Toys and Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to bring forward legislative proposals to restrict the sale of toy knives.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","290440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145451","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-10-08","<p>The Department’s data collection exercise is aimed at enabling the government to build a picture of external wall systems in use on high rise residential buildings. This exercise will collect data on residential buildings 18 metres and over covering private and social buildings, student accommodation and hotels. There are currently no plans to call for samples of building material or insulation as part of the data gathering exercise.</p><p>However, as part of the Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) screening program funded by the government, the Building Research Establishment has been requested to catalogue samples which are identified as non-ACM materials as detailed in the response to Question UIN 234718 on 27 March 2019.</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey",,"2019-10-08T10:15:49.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145451/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145451/answer","Tatton","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145451/answer/previousversion/136261","Biography information for Esther McVey","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-24","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, for what reasons his Department has not issued a call for samples of building materials used in (a) external wall materials and (b) insulation of high rise buildings as part of the recent data collection exercise on external wall systems in high-rise residential buildings.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","290345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145452","Home Office","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Home Secretary has not yet received the final report from Wendy Williams. On receipt, it will be published as soon as practicable.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-10-07T11:28:58.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145452/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145452/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-24","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has received the final report of the Windrush lessons learned review.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","290346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145453","Department for Education","false","2019-09-30","<p>The number and proportion of children in state-funded primary and secondary schools known to be eligible for and claiming free school meals in each local authority are published in the annual ‘School, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical releases published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a>.</p><p>The most recent data covering January 2019 can be found in Table 4c here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019</a>.</p><p>The underlying data to these releases provides this information at school level.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","290442","2019-09-30T16:12:02.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145453/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145453/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-24","Free School Meals: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in primary schools in Barnsley were eligible for free school meals in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","290441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145454","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-09-30","<p>As with any building refurbishment, for insulation delivered under energy efficiency schemes, including ECO, it is the responsibility of anyone carrying out building work to ensure compliance with the 2010 Building Regulations. Approved Document B volume 1: Dwellings (2019 edition) on fire safety covers, among other matters, fire spread. Local Authorities are responsible for enforcement.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng",,"2019-09-30T15:37:31.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145454/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145454/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-24","Housing: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether there is a requirement that insulation installed under the Energy Company Obligation scheme be of limited combustibility.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","290347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145455","Department for Education","false","2019-09-30","<p>The number and proportion of children in state-funded primary and secondary schools known to be eligible for and claiming free school meals in each local authority are published in the annual ‘School, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical releases published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a>.</p><p>The most recent data covering January 2019 can be found in Table 4c here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019</a>.</p><p>The underlying data to these releases provides this information at school level.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","290441","2019-09-30T16:12:02.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145455/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145455/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-24","Free School Meals: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in secondary schools in Barnsley were eligible for free school meals in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","290442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145456","Department for Education","false","2019-10-03","<p>The number of apprenticeship starts in Barnsley local authority in each year since 2010/11 can be found in the table attached.</p><p>More detailed breakdowns of starts in local areas, by characteristics such as age, level and sector subject area are available in the further education data library:<br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships</a>.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-10-03T20:00:46.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145456/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145456/answer","290443_Apprenticeship_starts_and_population_estimates_for_Barnsley_by_academic_year.xls","290443_Apprenticeship_starts_and_population_estimates_for_Barnsley_by_academic_year.xls","290443_Table","290443_Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145456/answer","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145456/answer/previousversion/136856","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","60","Education","Education","2019-09-24","Apprentices: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many apprenticeships starts there were in Barnsley in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","290443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145457","Department for Education","false","2019-09-30","<p>The department does not publish the number of children eligible for free school meals (FSM) entering higher education at a local authority level.</p><p>The department publishes information at a local authority level on the proportion of students who entered higher education by age 19 who were eligible for FSM at age 15 in state-funded and special schools.</p><p>The attached table shows the estimated percentage of pupils from state-funded and special schools with free school meal status that entered higher education by age 19 for Barnsley. The percentage has increased from 4% in 2005/06 to 10% in 2016/17.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-09-30T16:40:35.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145457/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145457/answer","290444 table FSM pupils entering HE age 19 .pdf","290444 table FSM pupils entering HE age 19 .pdf","290444_table","290444_table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145457/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-24","Free School Meals: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children in secondary schools in Barnsley eligible for free school meals went on to higher education in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","290444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145458","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-09-30","<p>Leaving the EU requires musicians and performers to adapt their current processes as they travel to and work in the EU. We have engaged extensively with stakeholders to ensure we fully understand these changes and to support the sector with their preparations..</p><p> </p><p>We have also worked extensively with colleagues across government to ensure musicians and performers’ interests are being considered as we prepare to exit the EU. Specific advice regarding travel and working abroad can be found on the Government’s <a href="https://www.gov.uk/brexit" target="_blank">Get Ready For Brexit</a> webpage.</p><p> </p><p>We are ensuring that latest guidance and updates regarding how organisations can best prepare for travelling and working internationally forms a key part of our business readiness preparations. My department is holding bespoke arts industry workshops designed to support individuals and organisations in the arts, culture and heritage sectors as they prepare. The government is also holding nationwide events offering tailored guidance and support which are open to all, to help prepare for Brexit.</p><p> </p><p>The Association of British Orchestras and UK Theatre have also been granted Government funding to provide industry briefings, open to those in their sectors and beyond.</p><p> </p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately",,"2019-09-30T14:57:06.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145458/answer","Biography information for Helen Whately","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145458/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-24","Entertainers: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will publish guidance for musicians and other performers on (a) travelling and (b) working in EU countries in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","290400"
